text_Pegmatite: Pegmatite seems to have irregular shapes and odd shaped discolorations. Splotchy is a word that comes to mind. The colors have some significant contrast, and the splotches seem to be darker in color.
text_Peridotite: For Peridotite, I noticed speckled patterns in some different shades.

text_Basalt: On some of the Basalt samples, the rocks look like they could be slightly smooth. There seems to be less detailed speckles throughout the rocks. They seem more monochromatic.
text_Gabbro: Gabbro seems to have an interesting texture to the surface. The colors seem to range from grey to brown, so I think that texture might be what sets Gabbro apart.

text_Andesite: Andesite appears to have unique colors and speckles. The colors are varied. The texture looks interesting.
text_Diorite: Diorite seems to have some glossy effect that might set it apart from other rocks. Intense and consistent speckling throughout.

text_Peridotite: The texture and patterns are less consistent on Peridotite. The shapes are fairly rough and the texture doesn't look smooth.
text_Diorite: Diorite seems to have starker colors and glossy sheen. Very consistent speckles all over the rocks.

text_Pegmatite: What stands out about Pegmatite is the dramatic black splotches and irregular shapes.
text_Andesite: Tiny speckles. Some of the speckles are rectangular and remind me of sprinkles, but less colorful and fun. There are irregularities in the speckling pattern on Andesite rocks. The colors of the rocks can vary from gray to brown. Reminds me a little of the epoxy coating you can get on garage floors.

text_Peridotite: Peridotite rocks look to be mostly brown and rough. The texture is what stands out to me with some different colors throughout, but not in an organized pattern.
text_Andesite: I think Andesite stands out because of that consistent speckled look. Although not vibrant, the colors of the speckles stand out more than the other rocks I have looked at.

text_Peridotite: In a few samples of Peridotite, I am seeing some sheen on parts of the rock. Reminds me a bit of a geode, though it is hard to tell on the computer screen. The texture on Peridotite appears rough.
text_Andesite: Another feature I notice about Andesite is that some of the faces are smooth instead of rounded.

text_Peridotite: Peridotite has less consistent patterns and appears to be mostly brown and tan.
text_Diorite: Diorite has much more distinctive colors and marbling pattern. The rocks are more striking and varied in appearance.

text_Basalt: Basalt appears to vary in color from brown to grey, and has a smooth face with sharp lines even though it can have small craters in it. It doesn't appear to have speckling or marbling.
text_Gabbro: Gabbro appears to have more marbling, but not quite speckled patterns. The texture looks rough.

text_Gabbro: The shapes of Gabbro appear to be more like a chunk, more block-like than Andesite. There is color variation, but not defined.
text_Andesite: Andesite has more pronounced speckles and color variation. The rocks look to be smoother than Gabbro.

text_Peridotite: Brown with some shimmer in places. Not a consistent pattern to it.
text_Diorite: More consistent patterns, with more shimmer than Andesite. Colors are more striking.

text_Peridotite: Brown, with some shimmer inconsistently. Very rough-looking texture.
text_Andesite: Texture looks rough, but the distinguishing effect is the color variation of the speckles and the smooth/flat face of the rock. Andesite samples seem to have sharper edges.
